\section{Introduction}

Genotype Conditional Association Test (GCAT) is a test for genetic association that is powered by Logistic Factor Analysis (LFA)~\cite{Hao2013}. 
LFA is a method of modeling population structure in a genome wide association study.
We have shown that GCAT (add citation when preprint/pub available) tests for association between SNP genotypes and a trait (either quantitative or binary) and is robust to confounding from population structure, given that LFA models structure accurately.

\section{Sample usage}

We include a sample dataset with the package. \texttt{sim\_geno} is a simulated genotype matrix. \texttt{sim\_trait} is a simulated trait. 
There are 10,000 SNPs and 1,000 individuals. The first five SNPs are associated with the trait. 
This simulations were done under the Pritchard-Stephens-Donnelly model with $d=3$, with Dirichlet parameter $\alpha=0.1$ and variance allotment in the trait corresponding to $5\%$ genetic, $5\%$ environmental, and $90\%$ noise. 
This dataset is simulated under identical parameters as the PSD simulation in Figure 2 of the paper (add citation when preprint/pub available), except that we have adjusted the size of the simulation to be appropriate for a small demo.

<<preamble>>=
library(lfa)
library(gcat)
dim(sim_geno)
length(sim_trait)
@

\subsection{\texttt{gcat}}

The first step of \texttt{gcat} is to estimate the logistic factors:

<<lfa>>=
LF = lfa(sim_geno, 3)
dim(LF)
@

Then, it is simple call of the \texttt{gcat} function:

<<gcat>>=
gcat_p = gcat(sim_geno, LF, sim_trait)
@

We can look at the p-values for the associated SNPs:

<<gcat2>>=
gcat_p[1:5]
@

And also plot the histogram of the unassociated SNPs:

<<fig1>>=
library(ggplot2)
dat = data.frame(gcat_p[6:10000])
colnames(dat) = "gcat_p"
ggplot(dat, aes(gcat_p, ..density..)) + geom_histogram(binwidth=1/20) + theme_bw()
@

